sentences: Wilson joined the Cavaliers after his discharge from Goodfellow Air Force Base in San Angelo, Texas, in 1962.
"Last Kiss" became a hit in June 1964, it reached the top 10 in October of that year, eventually reaching number two on the Billboard Hot 100.

In October 1964, the British music magazine NME reported that Wilson had himself been involved in an auto accident near Lima, Ohio, in which his 27-year-old record producer, Sonley Roush, was killed, and Wilson was seriously injured.
Wilson, with or without the Cavaliers, continued to release records until 1978.
Wilson died on October 4, 1991, at the age of 49, from alcoholism and complications from diabetes.
He started working offshore oilfield in late 1970s and 1980s in the Gulf of Mexico.

"Last Kiss" became a hit in June 1964, it reached the top 10 in October of that year, eventually reaching number two on the Billboard Hot 100.
